    <h1 class="text-center">Leave Policy</h1>

    <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> This policy aims to describe the number of leaves that an employee is entitled to in the financial year. Employees should understand that leave is a privilege and not an automatic right. The company reserves the authority to approve or reject any leave request based on business needs and the specific circumstances at the time.</p>

    <p>The following are types of leave for employee benefits.</p>

    <h2 class="section-title">1. Casual Leave</h2>
    <p>It is a type of paid time off that employees can use for short-term, unexpected absences from work, often for personal reasons or emergencies.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Entitlement: 6 days/year, credited pro-rata.</li>
      <li>Approval: Prior approval is required unless it's an emergency.</li>
      <li>Restrictions include advance notice, blackout periods, and staffing limits.</li>
      <li>Duration: Max 2 consecutive days. Beyond that, it's considered planned leave.</li>
      <li>Unused leave dissolves at year-end.</li>
      <li>Can be adjusted with earned or sick leave.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="section-title">2. Sick Leave</h2>
    <p>Paid time off for illness or medical conditions.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Entitlement: 6 days/year, pro-rata.</li>
      <li>Medical proof required if leave exceeds 2 days.</li>
      <li>Unused leave dissolves at year-end.</li>
      <li>Adjustable with earned or casual leave.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="section-title">3. Planned Leave</h2>
    <p>Pre-scheduled leave approved in advance.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Entitlement: 15 days/year, pro-rata.</li>
      <li>Written approval required 3 days in advance.</li>
      <li>Unused leave may be carried forward or encashed.</li>
      <li>Adjustable with casual or sick leave.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="section-title">4. Short Leave</h2>
    <p>Short leave for up to 2 hours during work hours for urgent personal tasks.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Allowed once per month.</li>
      <li>Cannot be carried over to the next month.</li>
      <li>Requires manager approval.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="section-title">5. Menstrual Leave</h2>
    <p>For female employees to take time off during menstruation.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Eligible once a month, self-declared.</li>
      <li>Requires prior approval.</li>
      <li>Misuse will attract disciplinary action.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="section-title">6. Maternity Leave</h2>
    <p>Paid leave before and after childbirth.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Full-time Employees:</strong> 26 weeks if completed 80 days in the last 12 months; 12 weeks for third child; 6 weeks for miscarriage; 2 weeks for tubectomy.</li>
      <li><strong>Contractual Employees:</strong> Up to 6 months or contract duration (whichever is shorter), for up to 2 children.</li>
      <li><strong>Exceptions:</strong> Adoption (12 weeks), Surrogacy (12â€“26 weeks), Post-pregnancy complications (1 month extra).</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="section-title">7. Paternity Leave</h2>
    <p>15 days of paid leave post-childbirth or adoption (up to 2 children) for male employees, after 80 days of service.</p>

    <h2 class="section-title">8. Unpaid Leave</h2>
    <p>When no paid leave balance is available, employees may apply for unpaid leave.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Limits: 2 days/month, 4/quarter, 6/half-year, 10/year.</li>
      <li>Weekly offs during LWP are also unpaid.</li>
      <li>Manager approval required.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="section-title">9. Bereavement Leave</h2>
    <p>Granted on the death of immediate family members (parents, siblings, spouse, children, grandparents).</p>
    <ul>
      <li>4 consecutive days/year, only once annually.</li>
      <li>Manager must be notified immediately.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="section-title">10. Restricted Leave</h2>
    <p>2 paid days/year for regional/state-specific festivals.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Prior manager approval required.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="section-title">Other Information</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Unauthorized absence leads to disciplinary action.</li>
      <li>More than 3 days of unnotified leave is considered resignation.</li>
      <li>Leave must be applied for and approved via the portal.</li>
      <li>Leaves during notice period extend the notice duration.</li>
      <li>Leave encashment is calculated at payroll/final settlement.</li>
      <li>4 policy violations may lead to termination.</li>
      <li>Travel must be pre-booked; delays not accepted without proof.</li>
      <li>Medical leaves over 2 days require documentation.</li>
      <li>Employees should plan for daily needs and have backups.</li>
      <li>Policy is subject to change by management as needed.</li>
    </ul>

